{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f59a0869-fa36-481a-8a8b-0efe6cdf601b","content":"This repo doesn't contain documentation on that topic, but here's the general guidance:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n2. **Reproduce the crash.** Core files are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP isn't blocking core dumps and the target volume has space. On newer macOS, you may need:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> ./your-app\n   ```\n\n6. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4` environment variables before running — though these rely on `createdump` being present in the runtime.\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't ship `createdump`, the OS-level core dump (steps 1–5) is your primary recovery path.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"35ab0780-56ee-4085-b5a7-0bfe9014aedc","outputTokens":356},"id":"3aaced91-dbf0-4d22-8a6b-b4cd2f59a6e1","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:02:41.449Z","parentId":"6d1be317-0377-4c6e-a359-cf940fbe242e"}
